Hereâ€™s a compact and practical firewalld cheat sheet (useful for Linux admins / DevOps) ðŸ”¥ðŸ§±

ðŸ”¹ Service Management
systemctl start firewalld
systemctl stop firewalld
systemctl restart firewalld
systemctl reload firewalld
systemctl enable firewalld
systemctl disable firewalld
systemctl status firewalld

ðŸ”¹ Check Firewall Status
firewall-cmd --state
firewall-cmd --get-active-zones
firewall-cmd --list-all

ðŸ”¹ Zones
firewall-cmd --get-zones
firewall-cmd --get-default-zone
firewall-cmd --set-default-zone=public


Assign interface to zone:

firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-interface=eth0

ðŸ”¹ Services

List available services:

firewall-cmd --get-services


Allow a service:

firewall-cmd --add-service=http
firewall-cmd --add-service=https --permanent


Remove a service:

firewall-cmd --remove-service=http

ðŸ”¹ Ports

Open port:

firewall-cmd --add-port=80/tcp
firewall-cmd --add-port=3306/tcp --permanent


Remove port:

firewall-cmd --remove-port=80/tcp


List ports:

firewall-cmd --list-ports

ðŸ”¹ Rich Rules (Advanced)

Allow specific IP:

firewall-cmd --add-rich-rule='rule family="ipv4" source address="192.168.1.10" accept'


Allow port from IP:

firewall-cmd --add-rich-rule='rule family="ipv4" source address="10.0.0.5" port port="22" protocol="tcp" accept'


Remove rich rule:

firewall-cmd --remove-rich-rule='RULE_HERE'

ðŸ”¹ Permanent vs Runtime

Runtime (default) â†’ lost after reboot

Permanent â†’ survives reboot

Apply permanent changes:

firewall-cmd --reload

ðŸ”¹ Masquerading (NAT)
firewall-cmd --add-masquerade
firewall-cmd --add-masquerade --permanent

ðŸ”¹ Forwarding
firewall-cmd --add-forward-port=port=80:proto=tcp:toport=8080

ðŸ”¹ Remove Everything (Zone Reset)
firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-service=http
firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-port=80/tcp

ðŸ”¹ Debugging
firewall-cmd --list-all
firewall-cmd --list-services
firewall-cmd --list-rich-rules

ðŸ”¹ Quick Example (Open HTTP Permanently)
firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent
firewall-cmd --reload
